{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Dependencies (STACKED — review with --ref HEAD)\nBuilds on **ddbe** (identity + mappings) and **264f** (`resolve_mapping`), committed\non this branch, not yet on origin/main. Review with `--ref HEAD`.\n\n## Context\nAn inbound external user (e.g. a Jira assignee/reporter with an `accountId` +\n`displayName`) that has NO local identity mapping mints a PLACEHOLDER identity\nstoring the raw `(provider, external_id, display_name)`. Re-running resolution after\na real mapping appears UPGRADES the placeholder in place — idempotently, one identity\nnot two — keyed on the provider's stable opaque id (Gitea's OriginalAuthorID\ndiscipline).\n\n## Why\nWhen rebar pulls a Jira ticket, its assignee/reporter/comment authors are external\nJira users we may not yet know. Minting a durable placeholder (keyed on the stable\naccountId) preserves attribution without guessing an email, and lets a later real\nmapping enrich the SAME identity rather than forking a duplicate.\n\n## What\n### 1. Resolve-or-mint seam (`src/rebar/_commands/identity.py`)\n`ensure_identity_for(provider, external_id, display_name, *, repo_root=None) -> str`:\n- IDEMPOTENT resolve-first: call `resolve_mapping(provider, external_id, repo_root=...)`\n  (264f). If it returns an existing identity id, RETURN it (do NOT create a second) —\n  this is what makes a re-run yield ONE identity. Optionally UPGRADE: if that identity\n  is still a placeholder and `display_name` is non-empty and differs from its current\n  title, update the title in place (`edit_ticket`) — the upgrade path.\n- Else MINT a placeholder: `create_identity(name=display_name or external_id,\n  email=\"\", mappings=[{\"provider\":provider, \"external_id\":external_id}], ...)` marked\n  as a placeholder via a `placeholder` tag (so `is_placeholder(id)` and validate/UX\n  can tell ghosts from real identities). Return the new id.\n- Never raises for a lookup problem (a resolve failure falls through to mint).\n- `is_placeholder(identity_id, *, repo_root=None) -> bool` helper (the `placeholder`\n  tag is present).\n- The mapping key is ALWAYS the provider's opaque `external_id` (never email), so the\n  resolve/upgrade is provider-neutral (works for jira/github/gitea alike).\n\n### 2. Placeholder → real upgrade\nWhen a real mapping/identity is later established for the same `(provider,\nexternal_id)` — either a subsequent `ensure_identity_for` with a better\n`display_name`, or an operator enriching the identity (email/keys) and removing the\n`placeholder` tag — the SAME identity id is reused (resolve-first keys on\n`external_id`). A test adds a real name/email to the placeholder, re-runs\n`ensure_identity_for(same provider/external_id, ...)`, and asserts exactly ONE\nidentity exists for that mapping (not two) and it is the upgraded record.\n\n### 3. Inbound reconciler wiring (`apply_inbound_records.py`)\nWhere the inbound apply reads a Jira user field (assignee/reporter — currently\n`_extract_name(fields[\"assignee\"])` at ~lines 113/258, which pulls only the\n`displayName`), resolve the inbound user through `ensure_identity_for(\"jira\",\n<accountId>, <displayName>)` so an unmapped inbound user mints/reuses a placeholder\nidentity and the local attribution references a stable identity. Keep the existing\nname extraction as the human-readable fallback; the identity minting is additive and\nbest-effort (a missing accountId falls back to the name-only behavior without\nfailing the inbound apply).\n\n## Scope\nIn: `ensure_identity_for` + `is_placeholder` (idempotent resolve-or-mint, keyed on\nexternal_id, placeholder tag, in-place upgrade) and the inbound-apply wiring. Out:\noutbound mapping (264f), enforcement (3183). Concurrency: minting is idempotent for\nSEQUENTIAL re-runs (resolve-first); the reconciler applies inbound records single-\nwriter, so no concurrent double-mint of the same accountId is expected.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `ensure_identity_for(\"jira\", <accountId>, <displayName>)` on an accountId with\n  no existing mapping creates a placeholder identity whose title is the displayName,\n  whose `mappings` contains `{\"provider\":\"jira\",\"external_id\":<accountId>}`, and which\n  `is_placeholder` reports True (test).\n- [ ] Re-running `ensure_identity_for` with the SAME `(provider, external_id)` returns\n  the SAME identity id and does NOT create a second — a test asserts exactly ONE\n  identity maps that accountId (list/search count == 1) after two calls, even when the\n  second call supplies a different display_name (which upgrades the title in place).\n- [ ] The mapping key is the provider's opaque `external_id` (not email), so an\n  upgrade for a different provider/id is independent — a test with two different\n  `external_id`s yields two distinct identities, and the same `external_id` under a\n  different `display_name` still yields one.\n\n## file_impact\n- `src/rebar/_commands/identity.py` (ensure_identity_for + is_placeholder)\n- `src/rebar/__init__.py` + `src/rebar/_lib_writes.py` (export ensure_identity_for/is_placeholder)\n- `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_inbound_records.py` (resolve inbound Jira user via ensure_identity_for, additive/best-effort)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783862559469124001,"uuid":"6911966e-a21e-467d-a8ab-d5c12f72851b"}